#compdef aspeak
# =============================================================================
# aspeak — kxxt's "simple text-to-speech client for Azure TTS
#          API" — a Rust CLI for invoking Azure Cognitive Services
#          Text-to-Speech with both REST and WebSocket synthesis
#          modes, SSML support, voice / locale / quality
#          selection, custom output formats, and TOML-based
#          profile config.
#          Distinguishing from say (macOS), espeak (eSpeak NG),
#          festival, and other TTS CLIs by:
#            - DUAL SYNTHESIS MODES — `--mode rest` (HTTP POST)
#              or `--mode websocket` (streaming WebSocket via
#              tokio-tungstenite); websocket mode delivers
#              audio as it's synthesized for lower latency
#            - AZURE COGNITIVE SERVICES TTS — accesses Microsoft
#              Azure's high-quality neural TTS engine with 400+
#              voices across 140+ locales (en-US-AriaNeural,
#              zh-CN-XiaoxiaoNeural, ja-JP-NanamiNeural, etc.)
#            - SSML INPUT — `aspeak ssml '<speak>...</speak>'`
#              accepts full Speech Synthesis Markup Language
#              with <prosody>, <break>, <emphasis>, <voice>,
#              <mstts:express-as>, <phoneme> tags for fine-
#              grained control over pitch / rate / volume /
#              emotion / phonemes
#            - 5 SUBCOMMANDS via clap derive:
#                * text [--file]      — speak plain text
#                * ssml [SSML]        — speak SSML markup
#                * list-voices        — list available voices
#                * list-qualities     — list quality levels
#                * list-formats       — list audio formats
#                * config (edit/init/where) — manage profiles
#            - 4 OUTPUT CONTAINER FORMATS — mp3 / ogg / webm /
#              wav with quality levels per format; --format for
#              expert mode with Azure-specific format strings
#              (e.g. riff-24khz-16bit-mono-pcm)
#            - 4 LANGUAGES IN VOICE METADATA + 140+ FOR
#              SYNTHESIS — list-voices --locale en-US filters by
#              locale tag
#            - TOML PROFILES via dirs + toml — ~/.aspeak.toml
#              stores default auth + endpoint + voice + output
#              settings; --profile NAME switches between
#              profiles; --no-profile bypasses
#            - PROXY SUPPORT via --proxy URL — HTTP / SOCKS5
#              proxies for restricted networks; respects
#              HTTP_PROXY env var
#            - REGION-AWARE — `--region eastus` auto-resolves
#              correct REST + WebSocket endpoints; alternatively
#              `--endpoint` for full URL
#            - DUAL AUTH — `--token` (Azure auth token) or
#              `--key` (Azure subscription key)
#            - rodio FOR LOCAL PLAYBACK — `--output -` (stdout)
#              prints audio bytes; if --output omitted, plays
#              directly via rodio (`audio` Cargo feature)
#          Used by: Azure customers needing CLI TTS for shell
#          scripts (e.g. notification text → speech),
#          accessibility workflows, podcast / audiobook prep,
#          language learning, and as a reference implementation
#          of tokio-tungstenite + clap derive + tokio + reqwest
#          + serde + toml + rodio composition in Rust.
#
# Author:  kxxt (rsworktech@outlook.com) — Chinese-based Rust
#          developer, also maintains other Rust CLI utilities.
#          aspeak released ~2022; active development through
#          2026; current version 6.1.0.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/kxxt/aspeak
#          https://github.com/kxxt/aspeak/blob/main/src/cli/args.rs
#          https://github.com/kxxt/aspeak/blob/main/src/cli/commands.rs
#          https://github.com/kxxt/aspeak/blob/main/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     src/cli/args.rs + commands.rs — uses clap v4 derive
#          (well-documented elsewhere).  Headline library:
#          **tokio-tungstenite** (clap is documented across
#          hundreds of Rust completions; tokio-tungstenite is
#          the new variant being documented here, opening
#          Axis 18 — WebSockets).
# Library: tokio-tungstenite (https://github.com/snapview/
#          tokio-tungstenite, https://github.com/snapview/
#          tungstenite-rs — "Lightweight stream-based WebSocket
#          implementation for Rust" — Daniel Abramov + snapview
#          team).  Distinct from all previously-documented Rust
#          libraries by being:
#             1. RFC 6455 WEBSOCKET PROTOCOL — implements the
#                WebSocket protocol (handshake + framing +
#                masking + close codes + ping/pong + permessage-
#                deflate) per RFC 6455 (2011).  Distinct from
#                HTTP libraries (reqwest, hyper) which handle
#                one-shot request/response, not persistent
#                bidirectional connections.
#             2. STREAM-BASED API — WebSocketStream implements
#                futures-util's Stream + Sink traits:
#                  use tokio_tungstenite::connect_async;
#                  use futures_util::{StreamExt, SinkExt};
#                  let (mut ws, _) = connect_async("wss://...").await?;
#                  ws.send(Message::Text("Hello".into())).await?;
#                  while let Some(msg) = ws.next().await {
#                      match msg? {
#                          Message::Text(t) => println!("{}", t),
#                          Message::Binary(b) => process_audio(b),
#                          Message::Close(_) => break,
#                          _ => {}
#                      }
#                  }
#                Distinct from callback-based APIs.
#             3. SPLIT INTO SYNC + ASYNC CRATES — `tungstenite`
#                provides the protocol implementation in a
#                runtime-agnostic synchronous form; `tokio-
#                tungstenite` wraps it for tokio async runtime;
#                `async-tungstenite` similarly for async-std /
#                smol.  This factoring enables WebAssembly +
#                embedded use cases.
#             4. TLS BACKEND CHOICE — native-tls (OpenSSL /
#                SChannel / Secure Transport) or rustls
#                (rustls-tls-native-roots / rustls-tls-webpki-
#                roots) via Cargo features.  Default is
#                native-tls.
#             5. PERMESSAGE-DEFLATE COMPRESSION — opt-in
#                permessage-deflate via Cargo feature for
#                bandwidth-efficient WebSocket payloads.
#             6. CONNECT_ASYNC + ACCEPT_ASYNC — separate
#                client (connect_async) and server (accept_async)
#                entry points; both return WebSocketStream.
#             7. HANDSHAKE CALLBACKS — accept_async_with_config
#                takes Callback for inspecting Request +
#                modifying Response during handshake (useful
#                for custom subprotocol negotiation).
#             8. LOW-LEVEL Message ENUM — Message::Text,
#                Message::Binary, Message::Ping, Message::Pong,
#                Message::Close.  Distinct from higher-level
#                JSON-RPC abstractions (jsonrpc-core / jsonrpsee
#                build on top).
#             9. SNAPVIEW MAINTAINER GROUP — Daniel Abramov +
#                snapview team; the canonical Rust WebSocket
#                stack underlying axum's WebSocket support,
#                rocket-ws, warp WebSocket handler, and most
#                Rust WebSocket-using applications.
#            10. SUBPROTOCOL NEGOTIATION via Sec-WebSocket-
#                Protocol header — clients can negotiate
#                application-specific subprotocols (graphql-ws,
#                mqtt, etc.).
# License: MIT OR Apache-2.0 (tungstenite / tokio-tungstenite);
#          MIT (aspeak).
# Status:  tokio-tungstenite — 2,460+ stars on snapview/tokio-
#          tungstenite, ~80M crates.io downloads (TOP-100 Rust
#          crate); foundational WebSocket layer used by:
#            * axum (Tokio team's web framework, WebSocket
#              support)
#            * warp (Hyperium web framework)
#            * rocket-ws (Rocket WebSocket)
#            * tokio-rs/tokio examples
#            * paritytech/parity-bridges-common (cross-chain
#              bridge)
#            * mullvad-vpn-rs (VPN tunnels)
#            * aspeak (THIS — Azure TTS streaming)
#            * 5000+ Rust applications
#          aspeak — 499+ stars on kxxt/aspeak, used by Azure
#          TTS users + accessibility / language-learning
#          workflows.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 72 +
#                                                  AXIS 18 (WEBSOCKETS) OPENS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 72ND Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 71 to 72
# documented libraries (tokio-tungstenite via aspeak).  Rust **breaks
# the three-way tie** at 71 and goes SOLO at 72 (Rust=72, Go=71,
# TS-Node=71).  New leaderboard: Rust=72, Go=71, TypeScript-Node=71
# (Rust solo at the top).  Taxonomy now spans 393 cross-language
# CLI library variants across 96 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R653 Rust=71 (notify → Axis 17 OPENS) → R654 Go=71
# (fsnotify) → R655 TS-Node=71 (chokidar → Axis 17 1/1/1) →
# R656 96th language (Limbo) → R657 Rust=72 (tokio-tungstenite
# THIS — AXIS 18 OPENS) → expected R658 Go=72 → R659 TS-Node=72 →
# R660 97th language.  This is the 1st of 3 leader bumps in the
# current segment.
#
# This completion OPENS Axis 18 (WEBSOCKETS) — the 18th documented
# cross-language CLI library axis.  Axis 18 covers the cross-language
# pattern of "library used by CLIs to establish persistent bidirectional
# WebSocket connections" — applicable to real-time streaming TTS
# clients (aspeak), terminal multiplexer protocols (tmate / sshx),
# IoT device drivers, GraphQL subscription clients, MQTT-over-WS
# clients, gRPC-Web clients, and any CLI consuming a WebSocket
# server endpoint.
#
#   Axis 18 (WEBSOCKETS) variants:
#     - tokio-tungstenite (snapview/tokio-tungstenite) — R657
#       (THIS) — Rust RFC 6455 WebSocket protocol; Stream + Sink
#       trait integration; native-tls / rustls TLS; permessage-
#       deflate compression; Daniel Abramov / snapview ecosystem
#     - (Go variant pending in R658 — likely gorilla/websocket
#       the canonical Go WebSocket library, or nhooyr.io/websocket
#       the modern alternative)
#     - (TS-Node variant pending in R659 — likely ws (websockets/
#       ws), the de-facto Node.js WebSocket library used by
#       socket.io, GraphQL subscriptions, etc.)
#
# Axis 18 distribution: Rust=1, Go=0, TS-Node=0.  Will reach 1/1/1
# three-language symmetry by end of R659.
#
# Cross-language Axis 18 design analysis:
#   The "WebSocket client" abstraction is non-stdlib in all three
#   languages.  Rust's std has no networking layer beyond
#   std::net::TcpStream (no WebSocket).  Go's stdlib has
#   net/http but no WebSocket helpers (gorilla/websocket fills
#   the gap; Go 1.19+ has experimental x/net/websocket but
#   nobody uses it).  Node.js's stdlib lacks WebSocket entirely
#   (browser globals only); ws is universal.  Each language's
#   Axis 18 library handles RFC 6455 protocol details:
#   handshake, frame masking, ping/pong, close codes,
#   permessage-deflate compression, TLS — a clean axis with
#   minimal stdlib overlap.
#
# Axis distribution summary after R657:
#   * Axis 1  (Argparse):     Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 4  (Colors):       Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 5  (Progress):     Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 6  (Errors):       Rust=6  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
